replies.comment info:
@Aryana You're right that there were fewer forms of media at the time of WWI, but there were actually tons of newspapers!  This data, however, only comes from the New York Times - does that change your thinking at all?

Also, is there a way you could figure out whether the  headlines are counted in the thousands or not?  What numbers a graph is actually showing is a really important thing to consider!

(I hope you will return tomorrow to read the Reveal.  It will point to the article that this graph came from, and you will find some other interesting graphs in it too.)

@Jude Lucido 
I totally agree with so many of your points. The amount of coverage for each event has decreased as the years have increased because of the short attention span that people have. Relating to today’s wars, there’s just so much stuff happening in the world like new technology and inventions, school pressure, and disease outbreaks that we’ve been distracted from the supposedly large issue that is a war. The low headlines you mentioned could be an effect of news reporters not wanting to continue reporting on the same issue for 18 years straight. There’s 6570 days in that span of time and I’m guessing only 20 of them would be dedicated to coverage and updates on a war. Even that’s generous. 

On your point about people becoming accustomed to war, I’m not sure that people get used to being in war, I think we just forget about it. There’s been no sudden draft since 1973, so men and women in America don’t have to worry about anything relating to war anyway. This is especially true considering every single one of the wars mentioned was fought in another country. America was never directly affected by any of them, so there’s no need to go all out on media coverage. Even if reporters were to want to cover the issue, they wouldn’t have enough video footage since they would have to travel to other countries in dangerous war time, something I bet not many would do. So yes, everyone including the reporters stop caring, but I don't think we get used to war altogether.
